            .</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18280221-217-person1272">
                  JOSEPH 
                  GIBSON
               <interp inst="t18280221-217-person1272" type="surname" value="GIBSON"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280221-217-person1272" type="given" value="JOSEPH"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280221-217-person1272" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am foreman to James Pope, of <placeName id="t18280221-217-crimeloc1155">Edmonton</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18280221-217-crimeloc1155" type="placeName" value="Edmonton"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18280221-217-crimeloc1155" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18280221-217-off1153 t18280221-217-crimeloc1155"></join>. On the 31st of January a person said a man had taken a load of dung from the side of the dung-heap; I went to the prisoner's master, who sent it back that night; he lives two miles off.</p>
               <p>Cross-examined by MR. CLARKSON. Q. Is not dung difficult to identify? A. Yes; I found it in the prisoner's cart, three or four hundred yards off - the cart was standing still at the time; I do not know which way he was going. I know his master would take him back; I believe he was led into it.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18280221-217-person1273">
                  ROBERT 
                  BURT
               <interp inst="t18280221-217-person1273" type="surname" value="BURT"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280221-217-person1273" type="given" value="ROBERT"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18280221-217-person1273" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I work for Mr. Pope. On the evening of the 31st of January I saw the prisoner at the end of the dung-heap, loading dung into the cart; he took about half the small load; there was another man with him - I went and said, "What are you doing?" they said, "We have put a load down, and are taking it up again;" I said,"I dare say you are;" they went on, and I told the prisoner's master of it. I spoke to the watchman, and went after the cart towards London.</p>
               <p>Cross-examined. Q. Which of them were loading? A. The prisoner and the other.</p>
               <p>GUILTY. Aged 24.</p>
               <p>
